ATLANTA Lester Maddox,
avowed segregationist, defied the
new civil rights law again by re-
fusing to permit three Negroes
to enter his restaurant.


A crowd of 500 jeering and
cheering whites supported him
vocally as traffic was tied up.


Maddox told the trio ofNAACP
representatives, including two
ministers that you're not about
to enter. If you live 100 years
you'll never get a piece of fried
chicken here"


He also called his II Negro
employees to help block the en-
trance and told the men seeking
service that they all would lose
their jobs If they entered. Some
of Maddox's employees asked the
men to leave.

Rights Law Again

HOLLYWOOD NPD Oscar
winner Sidney Potter will play
a FBI agent assigned to track
down kidnapper on the East
Coast, in a new film called The
Seven File,' which will be filmed
soon.


Poitier's role in the new film
was announced last week by CO.
producers Ralph Nels on and Fred
Engel. Nelson and Engel will
produce the film for United
Artists.


"The Seven File" will team
Potter and Nels on in their second
effort in recent months. They
were also teamed in "Lillies of
the Field" which won Potter
HOLLYWOOD coveted "best
actor" Academy award.

PITTSBURGH, Pa. Gene
Mulberry was named retail
sales representative with Gulf
OTIS New York marketing d.
vision. He will service sales
accounts in the Bronx-Manhattan
sales area.


A native of Philadelphia, MIR.
Mulberry was graduated in 1860
from Howard University, where
he ajored in psychology. At
Howard, he was president of
Kappa Sigma debating society
and of the Wesley Foundation.
A member of the Army Reserve
Officers Training Corps, he later
served as a second lieutenant
of artillery at Forts Sill and
Dix. upon discharge, he worked
for the US. Post Office, the
Philadelphia Board of Education,
and Department of Public As
sistance prior to joining Gulf
as a sales trainee in December,
1868.

Police said friends of Cleve-
land Menefield, found him
kneeling on the floor ofhis apart
ment at 1926 E. Jefferson, his
head resting on his bed.


Officers said Menefield was
beaten with an instrument which
left two small holes In the top
of his head.


A neighbor told police he saw
Menefield in that position at about
8:45 pm. Saturday, but thought
the victim was alive.

lets from a 38 caliber pistol
are being checked in the FBI
laboratories. The bullets were
found in the bodies of the three
slain civil rights workers who
we're killed near Philadelphia,
Miss.


No arrests have been made.

men say the four Athens men

Murder warrants for them may

Evidence against the prisoners
will be presented during the week

NEW YORK = Roy wilkins,
executive secretary of the Ma
tional Association for the Adj
vancement of Colored People, has
been notified by White House
authorities that emergency first
aid and medical services in
federal hospital and health
facilities in Mississippi will be
made available to civil rights
workers in that state.


Lee White, a presidential aide,
in a letter, said the President
had asked him to investigate the
matter following receipt of
telegram from Mr.. Wilkins, DR..
Kenneth w. Clement, president,
National Medical Association:
and DR.. Alonzo VERIFY president,
New York City Public Health As
ISOLATION.


White said that under existing
policies of those Federal
agencies which operate medical
facilities, treatment is available
for emergency patients.


The wire was sent to Presi-
dent Johns on after night-riders
had shot into a church in Moss
Point, Mississippi, where a civil
rights meeting was being held,
wounding l6-year-old girl.

case against an elderly Negro
couple, did not realize they were
were signing a mortgage on their
home when they obtained loan.
was dismissed here last week In
circuit court.


In the hearing before Judge
lyric A. Boyer, 1t was revealed
that the defendants, Mr.. and Mrs.
Benjamin Dowdell, had limited
education and we're not aware they
signed a $4,000 mortgage on
their home when they obtained
loan from the Argus Corporation
on Jan. %, 1868.


Argus later assigned the mort
gage to the Florida Mortgage
Properties, Ltd, who sued the
couple.


The Dowdells wanted the money
to repaint their house, which
figures show cost 81 SOL .03.


The difference between this
figure and the $4,000 was
explained as a payment by Argus
of $3.50 to an attorney, which
was later applied toward $l40
in delinquent payments on an
other mortgage. The remaining
$40 was for an unexplained fee.
In addition the suit listed
$ll3.97 in redemption of tax
certificates.

Almost Lose Home
Signing Mortgage Note
